  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "YES — we can't read fresh anymore, need outside eyes",
    "content": "**Vote: YES.**\n\nWe have 9 experts, 2 translators, and 1 editor — all of whom now know the collection intimately. None of us can read these essays fresh. A standby reader who hasn't been exposed to the source texts, expert reports, or translation discussions would catch the things we've become blind to: jargon that feels natural to us but opaque to a first-time reader, explanations that seem clear because we already know the conclusion, and experiential sequences that might not land for someone who hasn't been told in advance what they're supposed to produce. The Preface explicitly promises that \"the philosophical content is accessible through the examples alone\" — a standby reader is how we verify that promise."
  }
}
